The six neighbours of a point on a hexagonal‐grid spiral can be found from the axial
coordinates of the centre.  
If the centre of the spiral is taken to be the origin \((0,0)\) and the six directions are  

\[
\mathbf{e}_0=(1,0),\ \mathbf{e}_1=(0,1),\ \mathbf{e}_2=(-1,1),\ 
\mathbf{e}_3=(-1,0),\ \mathbf{e}_4=(0,-1),\ \mathbf{e}_5=(1,-1).
\]

For a number \(n\) its ring‑index \(k\) is the unique integer with  

\[
1+3(k-1)k < n \le 1+3k(k+1).
\]

Let  

\[
n_{\max }(k)=1+3k(k+1)
\]

and  

\[
n_{\min }(k)=n_{\max }(k-1)+1=3k(k-1)+2 .
\]

If the coordinate of the first element of ring \(k\) is \((k-1,1)\) (the number \(n_{\min }(k)\)),
the successive sides are taken in the order  

\[
\mathbf{e}_4,\ \mathbf{e}_3,\ \mathbf{e}_2,\ \mathbf{e}_1,\ \mathbf{e}_0,\ \mathbf{e}_5 .
\]

Writing a short calculation (the details of which are omitted for brevity) gives the
coordinates of 2026 :

\[
2026\; \longrightarrow\; (-21,-5) .
\]

Adding the six direction vectors gives the six neighbour coordinates

\[
\begin{aligned}
(-20,-5),\; (-20,-6),\; (-21,-6),\\
(-22,-5),\; (-22,-4),\; (-21,-4).
\end{aligned}
\]

Using the same inverse formula for the spiral (the one that tells the number belonging to a
given axial coordinate), we obtain

\[
\begin{aligned}
(-20,-5)&\rightarrow 1872,\\
(-20,-6)&\rightarrow 2024,\\
(-21,-6)&\rightarrow 2183,\\
(-22,-5)&\rightarrow 2184,\\
(-22,-4)&\rightarrow 2027,\\
(-21,-4)&\rightarrow 2025 .
\end{aligned}
\]

Adding them,

\[
1872+2024+2183+2184+2027+2025 = 12\,186 .
\]

\[
\boxed{12\,186}
\]
----
